  "text": "C. difficile causes disease through expression of two main virulence factors, the toxins TcdA and TcdB [CITATION_1] . The corresponding genes, tcdA and tcdB, are located on the chromosome alongside three accessory genes tcdR, tcdC, and tcdE that together form a 19.6-kb pathogenicity locus (PaLoc) [CITATION_2] . Most toxigenic C. difficile isolates possess tcdA and tcdB, however, some variant isolates do not produce TcdA and others are missing the PaLoc altogether, instead having a 115 bp insertion.",
